        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Manjul Bhargava, Kiran Kedlaya, and Lenny Ng",
        "bbox": [
          0.3345864591613491,
          0.11627907015915184,
          0.671052630171358,
          0.13081395324201098
        ],
        "order": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_16",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Second solution: For any nonzero value of a, the two conics will intersect in four points in the complex projective plane P? (C). To determine the y-coordinates of these intersection points, subtract the two equations to obtain",
        "bbox": [
          0.5545112821190314,
          0.16715116269218697,
          0.92105262430954,
          0.2369186044688763
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_2",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A-1 The only such a are 2/3,3/2, (13 V 601)/12.",
        "bbox": [
          0.09398497225749441,
          0.1671511627265229,
          0.4398496171222047,
          0.183139535347605
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "First solution: Let C and C be the curves y = ax? + ax + 4 and x = ay? + ay + 24, respectively, and let L be the line y = x. We consider three cases.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12781954244612342,
          0.18452380962815546,
          0.4906015029298164,
          0.2281976740137817
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If C, is tangent to L, then the point of tangency (x,x) satisfies",
        "bbox": [
          0.12776764141262784,
          0.23536706330726495,
          0.4887217956980034,
          0.26034296329392875
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_17",
        "observed_type": "formula",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.5921052718558735,
          0.2514534880898949,
          0.8402255614148032,
          0.26744186071097703
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_5",
        "observed_type": "formula",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "",
        "bbox": [
          0.16130994423627157,
          0.2732558141305086,
          0.4172932334455665,
          0.30087209223316885
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_18",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Therefore, at a point of intersection we have either x = y, or x = - 1/a- (y + 1). Substituting these two possible linear conditions into the second equation shows that the y-coordinate of a point of intersection is a root of either Qi (x) = ay2+(a-1)y+1/24 or 2(x) = ay? +(0+1)4+25124+1/0.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5545112839094448,
          0.2790178573562147,
          0.9210526260999535,
          0.36631944412024287
        ],
        "order": 9
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0002",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001",
