  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0003",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_19",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_19",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If two curves are tangent, then the y-coordinates of at least two of the intersection points will coincide; the converse is also true because one of the curves is the graph of a function in x. The coincidence occurs precisely when either the discriminant of at least one of O1 or 22 is zero, or there is a common root of li and Q2. Computing the discriminants of li and l2 yields (up to constant factors) fi (a) = 6a2 - 130 + 6 and f2(a) = 6a2 - 130 - 18, respectively. If on the other hand Q, and &2 have a common root, it must be also a root of Qz (y) - 21(y) = 2y + 1 + 1/0, yielding y=-(1+0)/(20) and 0 = Qi (y) = - f2(a)/(240).",
        "bbox": [
          0.5545112901804268,
          0.3705357144832359,
          0.9191729384420345,
          0.5451388888158143
        ],
        "order": 12
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0004",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_8",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 3,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_8",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "which simplifies to 0 = 24x2 - 2x - 1 = (6x + 1) (4x1), or x € 11/4, -1/67. This yields a = 1/(2x + 1) € 12/3,3/25.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12781954866289924,
          0.4084302326349271,
          0.48872179870552207,
          0.45494186032776684
        ],
        "order": 13
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_9",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If C, does not intersect L, then Cy and C2 are separated by L and so cannot be tangent.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12969925480825842,
          0.4593023254465474,
          0.4906015054724391,
          0.486918604640662
        ],
        "order": 14
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_10",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If G intersects L in two distinct points Py, P2, then it is not tangent to L at either point. Suppose at one of these points, say Pi, the tangent to C, is perpendicular to L; then by symmetry, the same will be true of C2, so C1 and C will be tangent at P. In this case, the point P1 = (x,x) satisfies",
        "bbox": [
          0.12781954115539673,
          0.49273255870081845,
          0.49060151109241035,
          0.577132936558498
        ],
        "order": 15
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0005",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_20",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 2,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_20",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Thus the values of a for which the two curves are tangent must be contained in the set of zeros of fi and f2, namely 2/3, 3/2, and (13 $ V601)/12.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5563909863060612,
          0.5493551586903773,
          0.9210526380050044,
          0.5930232554949179
        ],
        "order": 16
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_21",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Remark: The fact that the two conics in P2(C) meet in four points, counted with multiplicities, is a special case of Bézout's theorem: two curves in P(C) of degrees m,n and not sharing any common component meet in exactly mn points when counted with multiplicity.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5582706734749294,
          0.5959302329740742,
          0.9191729340438677,
          0.6701388887106469
        ],
        "order": 17
      }
    ]
  },
