  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0007",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_22",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 1,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_22",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Many solvers were surprised that the proposers chose the parameter 1/24 to give two rational roots and two nonrational roots. In fact, they had no choice in the matter: attempting to make all four roots rational by replacing 1/24 by B amounts to asking for B~ + B and B= + B + I to be perfect squares. This cannot happen outside of trivial cases (B = 0, -1) ultimately because the elliptic curve 24A1 (in Cremona's notation) over Q has rank 0. (Thanks to Noam Elkies for providing this computation.)",
        "bbox": [
          0.5581674152053177,
          0.6758432538467403,
          0.9192629954764985,
          0.8183139534950389
        ],
        "order": 21
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0008",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001",
    "primary_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_14",
    "source": "text_cluster",
    "member_count": 2,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_14",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "or x = (-23 ‡ V 601)/72. This yields a = - 1/(2x+ 1) = (13 ‡ V601)/12.",
        "bbox": [
          0.1278195501666586,
          0.7165178572462023,
          0.49060151109241035,
          0.7470930237196981
        ],
        "order": 22
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001_15",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If instead the tangents to C1 at Pi, Pe are not perpendicular to L, then we claim there cannot be any point where C, and C are tangent. Indeed, if we count intersections of Cj and C (by using Ci to substitute for y in C2, then solving for y), we get at most four solutions counting multiplicity. Two of these are P, and P2, and any point of tangency counts for two more. However, off of L, any point of tangency would have a mirror image which is also a point of tangency, and there cannot be six solutions. Hence we have now found all possible a.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12593984319800317,
          0.7529069771005594,
          0.49060151260400175,
          0.9084302322549397
        ],
        "order": 23
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0009",
    "kind": "text_cluster_panel",
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2007_Solutions_2007s_page_001",
